        <updated>2021-05-28T08:57:47-04:00</updated>
            <summary>
                <![CDATA[
                     I started by cutting the back of the rear subframe off and welding on a new hoop to give a nice clean rounded "butt" to the bike. I realized there was a problem with the new hoop when I mocked up a seat with&hellip;
                ]]>
            </summary>
        <content type="html">
            <![CDATA[
                
  <p>
    I started by cutting the back of the rear subframe off and welding on a new hoop to give a nice clean rounded "butt" to the bike.
  </p>

    <figure class="post__image post__image--center">
      <img loading="lazy" src="https://paulnorthup.com/media/posts/1/rear-hoop-lg-2.jpeg" sizes="(max-width: 48em) 100vw, 768px" srcset="https://paulnorthup.com/media/posts/1/responsive/rear-hoop-lg-2-xs.jpeg 300w ,https://paulnorthup.com/media/posts/1/responsive/rear-hoop-lg-2-sm.jpeg 480w ,https://paulnorthup.com/media/posts/1/responsive/rear-hoop-lg-2-md.jpeg 768w ,https://paulnorthup.com/media/posts/1/responsive/rear-hoop-lg-2-lg.jpeg 1024w ,https://paulnorthup.com/media/posts/1/responsive/rear-hoop-lg-2-xl.jpeg 1360w ,https://paulnorthup.com/media/posts/1/responsive/rear-hoop-lg-2-2xl.jpeg 1600w"  height="1060" width="1024" alt="" />
      
    </figure>

  <p>
    I realized there was a problem with the new hoop when I mocked up a seat with some carpet foam. I figured a standard size caf√©/brat seat would look pretty good, so I went with ~2" of foam, but it looked horrible. The angle of the rear subframe on the LTD model of a KZ550 is steep to support a two-up "King and Queen" seat, not the style I was looking for.<br>
  </p>

    <figure class="post__image post__image--center">
      <img loading="lazy" src="https://paulnorthup.com/media/posts/1/ugly-seat-xl.jpeg" sizes="(max-width: 48em) 100vw, 768px" srcset="https://paulnorthup.com/media/posts/1/responsive/ugly-seat-xl-xs.jpeg 300w ,https://paulnorthup.com/media/posts/1/responsive/ugly-seat-xl-sm.jpeg 480w ,https://paulnorthup.com/media/posts/1/responsive/ugly-seat-xl-md.jpeg 768w ,https://paulnorthup.com/media/posts/1/responsive/ugly-seat-xl-lg.jpeg 1024w ,https://paulnorthup.com/media/posts/1/responsive/ugly-seat-xl-xl.jpeg 1360w ,https://paulnorthup.com/media/posts/1/responsive/ugly-seat-xl-2xl.jpeg 1600w"  height="1020" width="1360" alt="" />
      
    </figure>

  <p>
    Here is the ugly seat, with the tire mocked up for positioning. The ramp is longer than the flat section... yuck.<br>I spent some time thinking about the seat frame, mocking up different seat options with cardboard, etc. After a while, I got so frustrated with making no progress I cut off the hoop, chopped the rest of the rear seat frame off, and welded the hoop back on. this gave me a much more aggressive look, and the proportions really started to come together.<br>
  </p>

    <figure class="post__image post__image--center">
      <img loading="lazy" src="https://paulnorthup.com/media/posts/1/short-seat-2xl.jpeg" sizes="(max-width: 48em) 100vw, 768px" srcset="https://paulnorthup.com/media/posts/1/responsive/short-seat-2xl-xs.jpeg 300w ,https://paulnorthup.com/media/posts/1/responsive/short-seat-2xl-sm.jpeg 480w ,https://paulnorthup.com/media/posts/1/responsive/short-seat-2xl-md.jpeg 768w ,https://paulnorthup.com/media/posts/1/responsive/short-seat-2xl-lg.jpeg 1024w ,https://paulnorthup.com/media/posts/1/responsive/short-seat-2xl-xl.jpeg 1360w ,https://paulnorthup.com/media/posts/1/responsive/short-seat-2xl-2xl.jpeg 1600w"  height="1200" width="1600" alt="" />
      
    </figure>

  <p>
    If life gives you subframe lemons, chop them right out and don't worry about 'em.<br>Along with the subframe work, I grinded off the rest of the frame tabs I wasn't going to use and bent the old rear shock mount supports around the new hoop to keep the original lines of the bike. Happy with the progress so far.
  </p>
            ]]>
        </content>
